  "doc_id": "2455",
  "text": "Under isoflurane anesthesia (5% induction, 2-2.5% maintenance), an incision was made in the right maxillary gingivo-buccal groove of the rats. The infraorbital nerve was exposed and dissected free from the surrounding tissue. As previously described by Miyamoto et al 31 and Xu et al, [CITATION_1] the lateral half of the nerve was lifted from the maxillary bone and cut with scissors in some rats to produce a partial transection of the nerve (p-IONX); care was taken not to damage facial nerve branches. In other rats, a sham operation was performed but without any nerve injury. After the surgery, the wounds were closed by sutures. The animals were returned to their home cages and fed with mash and chow.",
